But if I run latest  f8409d4 I get a parsing error returned by ffmpeg;
[Parsed_crop_1 @ 0x4c86340] [Eval @ 0x7ffee8b86310] Invalid chars '\:ih*.63\:iw-(iw*.64)\:ih-(ih*.833)' at the end of expression 'iw*.63\:ih*.63\:iw-(iw*.64)\:ih-(ih*.833)'
Error when evaluating the expression 'iw*.63\:ih*.63\:iw-(iw*.64)\:ih-(ih*.833)'

You can see that FFMpeg is rejecting part of the string, I guess the escaping is broken?

The gulpFile.js 

```
gulp.task('uglify', function () {
    gulp.src(src)
        .pipe(concat('smart-table.min.js'))
        .pipe(uglify())
        .pipe(gulp.dest(disFolder));
});

gulp.task('concat', function () {
    gulp.src(src, { base: '.' })
        .pipe(sourcemaps.init())
        .pipe(concat('smart-table.js'))
        .pipe(sourcemaps.write())
        .pipe(gulp.dest(disFolder));
});
```
should be
```
gulp.task('uglify', function () {
    gulp.src(src)
        .pipe(concat('smart-table.min.js'))
        .pipe(sourcemaps.init())
          .pipe(uglify())
        .pipe(sourcemaps.write('.'))
        .pipe(gulp.dest(disFolder));
});

gulp.task('concat', function () {
    gulp.src(src, { base: '.' })
        .pipe(concat('smart-table.js'))
        .pipe(gulp.dest(disFolder));
});
```

Note that `'.'` in `sourcemaps.write('.')` is important, otherwise it not create an individual source map file.

I tried your solution for persistence with the latest version of smart-table.debug.js. I have the problem that every time I refresh the site the table jumps back to page 1 in the pagination.

I forked your stPersist plunkr:

http://plnkr.co/edit/gUVjELWEMpsQurww7683?p=preview

and just updated the smart-table.debug.js source. 

To reproduce the issue: Jump to a page greater the 1 in the paginator and press the refresh button. The table jumps back to page 1.

My solution would be following:

Change the stItemsByPage watcher at line 384 to

        scope.$watch('stItemsByPage', function (oldValue, newValue) {
          if (oldvalue !== newvalue) {
            scope.selectPage(1);
          }
        });

and comment out line 398

        // ctrl.slice(0, scope.stItemsByPage);

Could you please have a look. Thank you very much.

In the Flask example app (but not the Flask ME one), the `done` route is defined like this

``` python
@login_required
@app.route('/done/')
def done():
    return render_template('done.html')
```

In order for the `login_required` decorator to work, it must be "inside" of the `app.route` decorator. Currently the `done` route is accessible for non-authenticated users as well.

Hi!

In my projects i have a lot of code like:
```python
def setup_user(user_data):
    # Load data from DB


@bot.message_handler(commands=['some_command'])
def a(message):
    user = setup_user(message.from_user)
    # ...


@bot.message_handler(func=lambda m: True)
def b(message):
    user = setup_user(message.from_user)
    # ...
```

Middlewares function can transform it to something like this:
```
@bot.middleware()
def setup_user(message):
    message.from_user.data = # load data from DB


@bot.message_handler(commands=['some_command'])
def a(message):
    # User DB data in the message.from_user.data 

@bot.message_handler(func=lambda m: True)
def b(message):
    # User DB data in the message.from_user.data
```

Getting data about user from DB isn't the only possible function of middlewares. For example, when user sends location, bot getting lat/long. In this case developer just can create new middleware that reverse-geocoding user's location.

